        </td>
        <td width="30" align="right" valign="middle" nowrap>
			&nbsp;

<a href="showpost.php?p=433533&amp;postcount=19" target="new" rel="nofollow" id="postcount433533" name="19" class="pcount"><strong>#19</strong></a>

			
		</td>
      </tr>
    </table>
    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_433533">It's been pointed out that there are 2 general types of poisons -- damage and utility.  This post will address the utility poisons.<br />
<br />
The utility poisons (slows, snares, debuffs, etc.) have a lot of potential to help rogues to solo.  Let's be honest here.  With respect to soloing, rogues are one of the worst classes in the game.  Heck, we might be the worst class of all in that area.<br />
<br />
Utility poisons could also help a rogue bring some useful utility functions to a group -- slows, snares, debuffs, and such.<br />
<br />
To be truly useful the utility poisons need to be changed in a number of ways.<br />
<br />
They need to be the PoP era and beyond style poisons that effectively give you a buff that allows you to proc an effect for a period of time.  If I am soloing and I need to get the mob slowed to beat it, and if I'm using a pre-PoP era &quot;one-shot&quot; slow poison, and it doesn't stick (which happens quite a bit), then I'm not going to be happy with the results of my hunt.  I'll spend more time summoning my corpse in the Guild Lobby and looking for a rez than I will hunting.<br />
<br />
They need to be able to stick on mobs of any level.  If I'm using a slow poison and it won't stick on the worst mobs I am hunting because they are 1 level over the poison's cap, or if the slow poison I use while soloing is useless in higher level group content, then I'm not happy.<br />
<br />
Alchemy created potions have stacked in my inventory for quite a while.  The vials of poison need to stack in my inventory and they need to stack to more than 10.  A 20 stack would be a bare minimum.  The clumsy old method we have of combining poisons into &quot;multi-charge&quot; versions of the same poison using the &quot;coffin bottles&quot; summoned with our quested Grandmaster Assassin's Seal should just be abandoned and the Grandmaster Assassin's Seal should be given some other useful function.  Perhaps it could be equipped in our ammo slot and given some sort of focus effect function like increasing our poison proc rate, or extending the duration of our poison proccing buffs.  (This idea needs more input, but I think I'm on the right track here.)<br />
<br />
The duration on the poison proccing buffs we get from our poisons needs to be a lot longer than 10 to 15 minutes.  Durations of at least 30 minutes for the mid-level poisons and perhaps as long as 60 to 75 minutes for the top level poisons would be much better.<br />
<br />
The new alchemy model of a variety of general types of potions (instant heal, heal over time, mana regen, damage shield, etc.) and multiple levels of each type (Distillate of Celestial Healing I, II, III, IV, etc.) is a really good one.  The system of having the lower level ones easily and cheaply made from merchant sold ingredients while still being at least somewhat useful is also a really good idea.  That same general model would work very, very well for the utility poisons.<br />
<br />
For example, I can envision several levels of poisons that give me a buff that allows me to proc a melee slow effect on the mob.<br />
<br />
The first two levels (what I will call tier 1) would have slows in the range of 15 to 20%, have fairly low skill levels to make (perhaps 50 to 100) and cost very little to make from ingredients sold on poison merchants in the Plane of Knowledge as well as in or near starter cities where there are Rogues' guilds.  The proccing buff might only last 10 to 15 minutes.  The ingredients for these could also drop from low level mobs in zones where players hunt in their teens, 20s and 30s.<br />
<br />
The next few levels (what I will call tier 2) would have increased slowing rates up to, say, a 30 or 35% slow, and they would cost a bit more to make, but they'd still be made using merchant sold ingredients available pretty much everywhere.  The skill level to make them should be no higher than about 200.  The proccing buff might last 20 to 30 minutes.   The ingredients for these could also drop from low level mobs in zones where players hunt in their 20s, 30s and 40s.<br />
<br />
The next few levels above that point (what I will call tier 3) would have slows up to, say, 40 or 45% and they'd have one ingredient that would require a little farming, but the drops should be really common in a lot of zones starting with zones where players hunt in their 30s, 40s and 50s, and the mobs that drop the stuff should be plentiful.  If you make a rogue farm for 6 hours to make enough poison for a 1 hour hunt he is not going to be happy.  If a typical level 50 rogue can't head out alone and gather up enough materials for a weekend of hunting in under half an hour from the time he leaves the Plane of Knowledge or the Guild Hall to head out to farm the stuff to the time when he comes back to do the combines, he's not going to bother because he's just wasting time he could be putting to a more productive use in the game.  The proccing buff might last 30 to 45 minutes.  The skill level to make them should extend up to perhaps about 250 or 275.<br />
<br />
The last few levels of slowing poison (what I will call tier 4) would extend up to perhaps a 50 to 55% slow.  In addition, they might have significantly increased proccing rates, hate reduction effects so a rogue could use them in a group without constantly stealing agro from the tank, and resist modifiers to make them stick better on resistant mobs.  The top level or two could also have longer lasting proccing buffs (55 to 75 minutes) so a rogue doesn't need to click the darn things so often.  It goes without saying that the ingredients for these should get increasingly more challenging to farm, but they should still be reasonably common in a variety of zones from a variety of eras.  The cost of making these would be higher than the cost of making the lower level slowing poisons, but not so high that it isn't rational to make and use them.  These would be the hardest to make, with skill levels for the very best ones perhaps extending to above 300.<br />
<br />
The advantage of this system when applied to utility poisons is that it won't require constant revamps.  About the only thing that will have to be done to maintain it is to make sure that at least some mobs that people are reasonably likely to hunt in each new expansion drop some of the ingredients required for tiers 3 and 4.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
