    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_433535">It's important to learn from the mistakes of the past.  I'm going to discuss some of the more glaring errors made in previous poisons implementations.<br />
<br />
1. Single shot poisons.  It probably seemed like a good idea at the time, but frankly, with perhaps a few exceptions (which I will let other people mention) these haven't been useful in any real sense for a long, long time.<br />
<br />
2. Super rare dropped ingredients.  The Omens of War era poisons pretty much all had at least one insanely rare ingredient.  Months of hunting in the right places in the right zones typically wouldn't yield enough of some of the rare ingredients to make a single 5-shot version of some of the poisons.  What was the point of adding recipes to the game for expendable items that will almost never be made, much less used?  These poisons were only slightly better than the PoP era poisons and the ingredients for most of those were often common drops.<br />
<br />
3. Poison ingredients that sell for so much plat to merchants that almost nobody will ever save them for their rogue friends even if they know what they are for and how rare they are.  Remember those stupidly rare Omens of War era poison ingredients I mentioned a moment ago?  They also sold to merchants for so much that the rare few that did drop were generally sold to merchants.  The merchants then wanted to charge so much for them that it wasn't remotely rational to buy them to make poisons that only lasted for 10 to 15 minutes each.<br />
<br />
4. Poisons that are virtually useless when added to the game or within a few expansions.  Most of the damage poisons fit into this category because they simply don't scale with newer content.  Rogues in raiding guilds who are doing content from even an expansion or two ago can do upwards of 1000 dps without even using disciplines.  Using disciplines my own dps can burst into the 3000 to 4000 range.  When you do the math the best damage poisons in the game add maybe 10 dps or so to a rogue's output and to use them regularly requires hours and hours of farming in areas where I generally don't get much, if any experience.  That's time that I could have used getting more AA's and better gear that would add a whole lot more to my DPS than those poisons ever will.  So what's the point of those poisons?  Are they just there to be skill up paths?<br />
<br />
5. Poisons that have an ingredient that only drops from one type of mob in one zone and it's a mob for which there are never more than a handful of them up at once.  The best example I can think of off the top of my head is Stiffening Ergot which is made using a Heartsting Venom Sack and some other stuff.  The Heartsting Venom Sack only drops from heartsting scorpions in the Field of Bone.  There's only a few of these heartsting scorpions up at any given time and they don't always drop the venom sacks.  Given their spawn rate it could take several days to get even a single stack of these things so it's just not practical to waste time farming them.<br />
<br />
6. Poisons that don't stack in my inventory in any sense at all.  'Nuff said.<br />
<br />
Those are the mistakes I can think of off the top of my head.  Perhaps some other folks here can add a few more to the list.</div>
