    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_433590">It is already a given that we &quot;do DPS&quot;.<br />
 <br />
One issue facing rogues is that, for example, Berserkers do similar DPS and yet are far more useful in a solo/group and raid setting.<br />
 <br />
There are plenty of ways that our overall contribution to DPS can improve through novel application of poisons although our individual DPS has not changed. Part of the problem is that players are so used to a narrow definition of DPS - and yet the vast majority of those same players have no real concept of what makes that DPS go up or down, what their group is doing for DPS or how the death of a raid mob is ultimately hastened by the actions available to the group or raid.<br />
 <br />
Put very simply, if I have even a .5second cast time on any poison during a fight, my DPS associated with my blades will go down. If through the application of poison to the mob, he ultimately dies faster than if I had never casted / applied a poison then surely that is a good thing associated with a rogue and poison. The same argument can be made for the survivability of the rogue solo, in a group or in a raid. Dead rogues do no DPS.<br />
 <br />
One option is to make all poisons insta cast or prepared in advance. I prefer the option that allows for a lot of flexibility in designing a poison application system that ultimately allows mobs to die faster. If we continue to focus on an outdated or limited understanding of DPS - that it is purely tied to ratio - then we will continue to struggle as a one trick pony class limited to a static mob with a back for our one and only chance to top a parse.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
