</div>I would like to mention here that I agree 100% with this.  I don't really want to have to carry a bunch of ingredients and a mortor and pestle with me all the time.  My bags are already overflowing with various clickie-buff items I no longer wear but whose buffs are still situationally useful even on raids, illusion items, food, drink, various potions, a few 10-shot poisons, a variety of weapons, summoned throwing items, some utility items, a few quest items, and an assortment of other stuff.  If I had to devote a general inventory slot to a mortar and pestle all the time and another bag or two of storage to poison ingredients so I could make them on the fly I just wouldn't have much (if any) space left to carry mob-dropped loot.<br />
<br />
<img src="images/smilies/emote_frown.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Frown" class="inlineimg" /><br />
<br />
I generally carry 8 ten-slot, 100% weight reducing backpacks of various kinds with me these days including Masters satchels made with both my Smithing and Poison making trophies.  I have a collapsed mortar and pestle in one of my bags which allows me to do poison combines in batches in or near PoK by destroying the Master Toxicologist's pack to make room for the summoned mortar and pestle, and then get it back when I am finished with the combines by making a quick trip into the Bazaar with my trophy to summon a temporary bag, turn it in to the Gnome there, and then combine the item he hands back in the summoned mortar and pestle to make the &quot;rentable&quot; bag.  Then I swap that into the general inventory slot with the summoned mortar and pestle and destroy the summoned mortar and pestle which I no longer need.<br />
<br />
<img src="images/smilies/emote_smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Smile" class="inlineimg" /><br />
<br />
Frankly, making poisons in batches that would stack before I head out for a hunt would be <b><i>much</i></b> more convenient for me than having to make them on the fly in the field.  It's the way people generally make food, beverages, potions, and other similar consumables.  I should think that players would generally prefer to make their poisons that way, too.<br />
<br />
<img src="images/smilies/emote_smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Smile" class="inlineimg" /></div>
