    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_433641">Poisons are the only tradeskill whose products are not tradeable. This doesn't make sense. Even other class/race-only skills make tradeable products.<br />
<br />
If you make poisons usable by others, then the effects have to be worth it to others. Utility poisons are probably the best fit here.<br />
<br />
A compromise to the &quot;only rogues use poison&quot; might be that non-rogues have to buy &quot;Use Poison&quot; AAs if they want to take advantage of the special poison effects. Rogues would continue to naturally get this skill as they level up.<br />
<br />
The Alchemy model is a good one. Eliminate all the various poison names and use &quot;Snare I, II, III, IV&quot; etc. The tiered structure described above is a good place to start. Make use of the Master Sketch, GMAS, and Trophies to manage who can make what tier poisons, e.g. Tier I - no special item, Tier II - Master Sketch, Tier III - GMAS, Tier IV - GM Trophy.<br />
<br />
Associating poisons with non-weapon slots doesnt make sense. The only thing that touches a target is our weapons (including Range/Ammo), not our hands, face, wrists, etc. This would limit us to 2 contact poisons in effect at a time, but that's more than one.<br />
<br />
Potions should function very similar to spells. Use the Short Term buff box if needed. It should reliably function (i.e. rarely fizzle; use the same fizzle calcs as for casters) and last a useful period of time (e.g. 30 minutes). For me, the reliability is probably the #1 reason I don't use poisons; Poison effects need to be scalable to the expanded difficulty. Even with the difficulty of components, the OoW poisons might be worth it if they still worked on Level 80 mobs. Like spells, make it clear what level the poison affects.<br />
<br />
The idea of debuffs is intriguing. Enhance the group benefits, similar to how Thief's Eyes already benefits the group, or Puma/Panther. I still think some Bristlebane poisons might be fun... <img src="images/smilies/emote_smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Smile" class="inlineimg" /><br />
<br />
Potions are already semi-stackable in Coffin Bottles. Perhaps make coffin bottles hold up to 100 doses, and be able to add new doses into an existing bottle.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
